My target was BLRA. Five had been reported the previous day. I parked at the corner of Paseo Padre and Patterson Ranch Road and walked in, as the park does not open until 8. Three other birders had arrived in the general area to the west of the entry kiosk an hour before me but had heard only Soras and VIRA. I wandered the area and could easily pick out the calls of these two rails. The birders left but I stayed on. I remained in the area, listening, changing position slowly up and down the road. Along the marsh at the SE corner of the entrance to Quarry, I heard a BLRA. A small stone wall is at this corner, along with four mechanisms used to control the flow of water. I heard the BLRA two or three more times. Bird was first heard at 7:40. I remained a bit longer but the bird did not call again, but like most BLRAs, it was impossible to see.
Tides returning @ 4PM pushed the shore birds closer to the shore.

TRIP COMMENTS: Kimya Lambert, Dan Tankersley and I headed to the south shore of Lake Camanche.  It's been more than ten years since I''ve been there, and hadn''t remembered how large the lake is and how extensive the campground infrastructure is (30 minutes free access or $6.50 for day use--it''s a big area, so we opted for the day use).  Near the boat lauch/fueling station we were surprised to see a MEW GULL on one of the buoys.  It was the only gull in the immediate area (there had been a report from the Amador side on 12/3).  The Common Loon was a nice bonus, and there were several small groups of A. White Pelican adding up to 18.  It was very cold (we ate lunch in the car) then headed off to Flood/Waverly.
2 Common Loons, based on bill size and shape as well as face and neck pattern and shape.  Common Loons are found regularly every winter on Camanche Reservoir.

High tide, high wind.  From the end of Canal St, looking across to Brooks Island.  The Brants-dark breasts, necklace, white undertail coverts, smaller than CAGO- were in a flock of Canadas and Western Gulls, looking pretty ratty. The ELTE were hanging out with the large flock of at minimum 40 CAT. Both the terns and the Brant were at the western end of the island, seen from near the Honda parking lot.  Al DeMartini reported a single Brant from Miller-Knox Reg Park last week on Countybirds-I couldn''t find that bird when I went to look for it last week. This is the same general area, and there is a large eelgrass bed off the the North Richmond Shoreline.  These 2 birds look badly in need of a molt, much like the summering Brant that we saw a couple of weeks ago in Bodega Bay with Rich Stallcup.

What a red-letter visit to a park I had often dreamed of visiting, and finally reached.  Lovely place, amazing drive to get there.  Anyway, the Goshawk, if that is what it was, was clearly the highlight.  I almost wish I had any doubt at all in my head about this one, but I do not.  Size, voice, gizz, tail/wing ratio, plumage patterning, eyeline - I had the time to check everything, and I did so as responsibly as possible.  But it was not the only highlight.  Peggy found the singing Lawrence''s Goldfinch male, and then, along with two campers (Catherine and Monica), we saw our lifer Western Diamonback Rattlesnake - a highly desired sighting to see from the safety of our car!  We saw it spread over the entire road - had to be 5.5 to 6 feet in length.  Loved this place.  We''ll return.

TRIP COMMENTS: Howard King and I spent the morning along the southeastern shore of the Salton Sea in search of a Red-throated Loon that had been seen the previous week off the west end of Young Road.  We began our search by working along the seawall and dike roads between the western end of Bowles Road and Obsidian Butte.  We drove the various roads bordering the Sea and stopped numerous times to scan the offshore waters and the rocky shoreline.  Given that it soon became apparent that the loon was not present, we began searching the area more widely for whatever else we could find.  We did not really look at the land birds in the adjacent vegetation; however, we did see or hear a few birds along the way.  It was clear and generally calm but with an intermittent, trace (5 knot) breeze, and temperatures ranging from the low 80s to the low 90s.  7:45-10:20 am.

The only birding we did along the shore of the Salton Sea proper was along a short stretch between Obsidian Butte and the intersection of Lack and Lindsey Roads.  We began by accessing Obsidian Butte from McKendry Road and then scanning the bay from the promontory in the southeastern corner of the butte (10:20-11:10 am, for the entire butte).  While here, we were joined briefly by Ken Petersen and a few others.  After scanning the shoreline and bay east of the butte, we briefly checked the northwestern shore, where we quickly realized that the shoreline has moved some distance further out from where it had been the last time I visited this particular spot (so the lagoon was now high-and-dry).  We then doubled back and continued across the southern part of the butte and then south along the seawall towards Grubel Road.  We found quite a few birds on the flats here, including most of the small shorebirds that we saw in this area.  Upon reaching Grubel Road, we turned west and continued to the north end of Lack Road.  We again scanned the flats from Grubel Road (where we met Kurt Radamaker and several others), before continuing down Lack Road.  It was from here that we scanned the snags and offshore waters for a Neotropic Cormorant that had been seen intermittently during the past week or so.  After checking Lack Road south to Lindsey Road, we continued south towards Unit 1 (leaving this area at 11:40 am).  It was clear, with a mild breeze from the west, and temperatures in the upper 60s to low 70s.  10:20-11:40 am.----Note: just before we arrived, Kurt Radamaker and others saw an adult Mew Gull flying by the seawall near the north end of Lack Road.

TRIP COMMENTS: Given that we were already in the area, Brian Daniels, Leo Ohtsuki, and I checked a short stretch of the Salton Sea shoreline between the west end of Young Road and Obsidian Butte.  We began by driving out Young Road to the seawall, where we scanned offshore for some White-winged Scoters that I thought had been seen here on the Christmas Bird Count (but which may instead have been seen off Rock Hill).  We then continued north, following the seawall to Obsidian Butte, but with several stops along the way.  Our most productive stop was to scan the beach just west of the intersection of Lack and Lindsey Roads.  It was here that a Red Knot had been seen for about a week, and where Brian eventually found it today.  After studying the knot and the other birds on the beach, we continued north to Obsidian Butte, from which we scanned the bay to the east from a promontory in the southeastern part of the butte.  By this point, it was mostly cloudy, with the clouds high and thin, a mild (10 knot) breeze from the south, and temperatures in the low to mid-60s.  10:05-11:05 am.

Returning to the Imperial Valley, Guy McCaskie, Matt Sadowski, and I did our best to confirm the presence of four Neotropic Cormorants at Fig Lagoon.  We began by scanning the lagoon from the bluffs over the eastern shore, a good vantage point, but one from which the cormorants were mostly quite distant.  From here, we did a counterclockwise circuit of the lake, along the way scanning the birds in general but with a particular emphasis paid to the cormorants.  There were quite a few cormorants (including four adult Neotropic Cormorants), many egrets, and a good-sized flock of shorebirds, but not too many ducks or gulls.  We did not, however, spend much time at all looking for land birds.  Upon leaving the lagoon, we briefly checked the Rio Bend RV Park, but we did not find many birds at all during our brief visit (a calling male Red-shafted Flicker was probably our best bird here).  We continued to have high, thin clouds, but it was now calm, and with temperatures in the upper 70s to the low 80s (if not the mid-80s).  2:15-3:15 pm.

TRIP COMMENTS: After photographing Alkali Mariposa Lilies (Calochortus striatus) in Rosamond (thanks TEW!), Leo Ohtsuki and I arrived here at about 1130  - yep, the place is still open for birders and looks about the same. It was put up for sale this year (or was it last fall?) with a price tag of many millions (I think it was 15 million or so), but with expensive overhead (the monthly water bill was like 4 or so thousand dollars per month!) and very little revenue generating ability. Many think itll likely go bankrupt. They had recently laid off their employees and closed the place down, turning off all the water. Birders figured that was the end; however, they recently rehired some staff and turned back on some of the water. The place looked pretty much the same to my eyes, although the water levels were down and the nice creek (and fountain) to right and in front of stables was only mud. Kelli Heindel was present so we joined her. Steve Sosensky soon approached reporting lack of water and no animals at the petting zoo. The four of us then met a group of about 10 San Luis Obispo birders including Tom Edell, Maggie Smith, and Kaaren Perry. They told us of a Kentucky Warbler - one of Leos most wanted state birds!

TRIP COMMENTS: We saw the broad-winged hawk very well when it was soaring.  It was a light juvenile. We noticed it to our south, then it circled over us several times, and drifted off to the north.  Black under wing tips, mostly white chest, belly, and underwings, and dark streaks on the side of the head (for the most part, we saw the underside of the bird).  Most of the bird''s back was brown, although there some faint off-white markings on the wings that were evident when the bird was perched.  We got an extensive series of detailed photos of the bird in flight, and three distant shots of it perched, and would be glad to provide them on request.

Leo Ohtsuki and I came here for the Broad-winged Hawk. We intended first to bird at Lake Balboa but strong off-shore winds developed overnight (gusting to 25 or 30 mph), so searching for birds in trees appeared hopeless. We parked near the entrance to the Sepulveda Basin Wildlife Reserve and walked south into the field between Woodley Avenue and Haskell Creek. Several other birders were present and searching for the hawk. The hawk came in from the south, crossed Burbank Blvd and landed in large cottonwood tree along Haskell Creek. I was able to get a few photos of it sitting on a swaying branch before it took off and disappeared to the north. We spread out searching for it but couldnt relocate the hawk. Most returned to the trail on the east side of Haskell Creek that provided a wide view of the field near the intersection of Burbank Blvd and Woodley Ave. After about 20 or 30 minutes, the hawk came back over the field but fairly quickly disappeared into some thick riparian habitat on south side of Burbank Blvd. We could not relocate it from Burbank Blvd. We saw an interesting variety of raptors during our couple hours here.
Time: 0837-0928. Clear, mostly calm, 50 deg F.

TRIP COMMENTS: Weather: clear, calm, chilly (42-62 degrees F.)----Woke up early (0545 hours) and slowly got clothes and deodorant on. Braved the cold, ran to the bathroom, and grabbed breakfast, Then I went for a long walk. Headed out past the general store and down the road to the east end of the lake. I worked this part of the lake, often backtracking (why did I have to drop that stupid glove?!), until I reached the boat launch around 0845. Then I headed back into camp, ditched my jackets and gloves at the tent, and continued along the northern side of camp along the edge of the big sagebrush flat up to the loop road, birding the yellow pine forest. I headed back after about half an hour, barely making it to the Hodgon''s trailer in time for devotions. Still getting new species (I''m impressed by the numbers of migrants/disperers, e.g., MGWA, LISP, etc.)
SPECIES COMMENTS: Fly-by--gave some whistles, which is why I noticed it.

TRIP COMMENTS: Weather: mostly clear, calm, cool.----On 4/2/10, UNB was one of my critical stops for my biking big day. I got to the beach at dawn (though I did ride through UNB before dawn--nothing different, though TONS of birdsong), and then from there hit UNB for a couple hours in the late morning. I did fairly well. Ducks (except for CITE and BWTE) are WAY down. Shockingly, I MISSED AMWI there. There wasn''t a single one. I also missed Pintail and Redhead. However, I did manage to come through with a few lingering diving ducks--BUFF, both scaup. I cleaned up on shorebirds, missing only REKN and SEPL. I nailed all the rails (amazing numbers of Soras--must be migrating through.)
SPECIES COMMENTS: At the nesting platform near Shellmaker Island.

TRIP COMMENTS: Weather: mostly clear, calm to light breeze, cool (chilly after sundown.)----On 4/2/10, I concluded my biking big day at Irvine Regional Park. I frantically raced around for the first couple hours, scoring stuff like WODU, RNDU, WAVI, BTYW, etc. I covered pretty large parts of the park proper. Unfortunately, no matter how hard I tried, I could not find HUVI or WBNU. Migrants were also pretty scarce, but I scraped up BTYW and WAVI.----From about 1830-1910 hours I hiked up the Puma Ridge Trail and finally succeeded in getting good looks at a Grasshopper Sparrow with the help of the iPod. ----Then, I met dad near the park entrance and we rode over to the wash to look for nighthawks, etc. On the way we heard an early WESO. Things were slow at first (though calling RCSP and CACW), but then GHOWs started showing up everywhere, and a COPO called a couple times. On the way out we stopped and heard BNOW nestlings begging from the hollow sycamore near the train station.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Flyover just before sunset.

TRIP COMMENTS: Weather: cloudy, breezy, light rain part of the time, cool, humid----On 7/6/10, I rode my bike to Bolsa Chica to chase the reported Sooty Tern. I rode south of the boardwalk about a quarter-mile to scope the tern island and immediately spotted the bird. A beginning birder named Dwight was there and I showed him the bird. I birded here--mostly watching terns--until 10:00, when I headed over to the boardwalk and birded out to the first overlook until about eleven. A great morning! Bolsa Chica is always interesting. Lots of shorebirds in interesting transitional plumages, and I always need more work on tern identification. Seeing Royal and Elegants together is really a great way to learn.
SPECIES COMMENTS: One sitting on a distant snag past the second overlook. I couldn't be sure because of the distance, but it looked like it had a brownish wash on the nape, indicating a young bird (seems early.)

The Nelson''s Sparrow was in the pickle weed/spartina edge of the marsh with Belding''s Savavnnah Sparrows, common yellowthroats and Marsh Wrens. It was a smallish, stocky sparrow with a short tail. It''s most obvious feature was the orange face and breast. The auricular was largely gray with a distinct post ocular stripe. There was also a weak moustachial stripe.There wasn''t a white central stripe on crown like LeConte''s sparrow. The nape was gray, same as ear patch. The chin was buffy. there was extinsive streaking on the flanks that spread a little on edge of breast. Belly white.Bright red-brown wing coverts and white stripes on a datk back. Forgot to write color of bill/feet. There were 2 Audubon groups present today sop hopefully someone has photographed the bird. This is the 3rd or 4th time that I''ve seen this bird at Newport Bay.

The purpose of this visit was to witness the Yellow Rail observed here over the past 3 weeks. No observations had been published this week so Ken Burton and I were not certain the bird was still being heard. I didn''t see Jeff Seay''s 7/17/10 post until I returned.  We walked the trail to the noted location, about 200 meters beyond the north edge of open water to a point where a couple of crossed sticks were located next to the trail. We arrived at the X about 1630 hrs and immediately heard the nearby bird, about 20 meters away, estimated by triangulation of the sound.  We spent 10 minutes here then walked toward the north end of the meadow into Lassen NP then returned to the crossed sticks.  Ken first heard the 2nd bird, much further into the marsh, at least 70 meters away from the first and maybe a little south from perpendicular to the first bird.  Because the near bird was so close, it was difficult to hear the more distant bird until the nearer bird stopped calling.  We both heard both birds calling alternately and together. Definitely 2 birds.

Howard King and I spent most of the afternoon checking the wildlife area after Chet McGaugh reported an adult Ruff earlier in the day.  Given that Chet had seen the Ruff in the new ponds of the San Jacinto Wildlife Area Wetlands Project, this is where we concentrated our time.  The ponds on the wildlife area that now harbored most of the shorebirds were the ones on the north side of the road opposite the duck clubs; however, there were also now large numbers of birds on the duck clubs themselves, and these were generally distant and in bad light.  After scanning the first few ponds on the north side of the road, we continued further out the road to check the ponds along the eastern edge of the property.  Although the southeastern pond had harbored many shorebirds earlier in the month, this pond was now a little deeper, so there were only a few shorebirds present.  After checking the new wetlands, we exited the refuge and entered again through the main entrance.  On our way out to the old ponds in the northern part of the property, we stopped and walked a loop around the pond on the south side of the river where Chet had seen the Ruff.  After again missing this bird, we continued out to the northern ponds, along the way scanning several more ponds with shorebird habitat.  We then walked a loop around the central pond off the north end of the wildlife drive, after which we returned to the new wetlands complex.  Upon our return to the southern ponds we met Brad Singer, Tom Benson, and Doug Karalun, who also were having little luck finding the Ruff.  Howard and I ended our visit to the wildlife area trying to scan the many birds that were inside the duck clubs, but we were again unable to locate the bird for which we had been searching.  It was partly cloudy, with a mild (5-10 knot) breeze from the south or southwest, and temperatures that began in the upper 70s or low 80s dropping to the low 70s by the time we left this site.  1:50-5:50 pm.

TRIP COMMENTS: John Green, Bill Hopson, and I joined Brad Singer, Howard King, and Tom Benson for a day of birding at Desert Center, with our primary target being the relocation of the Yellow-green Vireo that we found here the previous day.  Given that there was a moderately intense thunderstorm for about the first hour of our visit, we first checked the lake and then drove out to the sewage ponds, but we began looking for the vireo as soon as the rain and wind tapered off.  We then spent over two hours scouring the southeastern neighborhood before driving over to check the southwestern part of the property.  I also checked much of the western half of the site while the others managed to relocate the vireo at about 11:30 am.  Given that they lost the vireo before coming to get me, I spent most of the rest of the day trying unsuccessfully to relocate this bird (though we did spend some time looking for an apparent Gray Catbird that John heard near the "sandbox").  Although we had quite a few migrants in the southeastern neighborhood in the morning, the vast majority of these birds seemed to disappear for the afternoon.  Even after some of the birds became more active late in the day, we never did relocate most of the warblers and vireos.  I have no idea if these birds left mid-day when the weather cleared or if they were inactive as a result of the heat, but I was not particularly hopeful that I would relocate the vireo given how few birds seemed to be present.  We checked the northern hedge one last time before leaving the site, but again with no sign of a catbird.  We arrived in the morning to find rain and an intense thunderstorm, but this cleared after about an hour to partly cloudy and then mostly clear skies by late morning.  There was some moderately strong (10-15 knot) wind associated with the rain, but this died down after the rain passed, leaving an intermittent, mild (5+ knot) breeze for the rest of the day (and, in fact, it was essentially calm late in the day).  I suspect temperatures ranged from the mid-70s to the low or maybe the middle 90s.  7:20 am - 5:25 pm.----Tom Benson reported seeing two Sabine''s Gulls flying by shortly before we arrived, but unfortunately, they did not stop.----Gray Catbird - 1 (?; calling; John heard three "mew" calls near the "sandbox" that he was quite certain were given by a Gray Catbird, but we were unable to locate this bird despite our spending a moderate amount of time searching the immediate and nearby vicinity);----Desert Cottontail - 4;--Western Whiptail - 1 (only John saw this one);--Desert Spiny Lizard - 1.

On my way home from San Diego, I met Howard King for a quick check of the wildlife area.  We began by checking the ponds of the new San Jacinto Wildlife Area Wetlands Project in the southeastern part of the property, where we found most of the avocets and stilts, and the vast majority of the shovelers.  After checking these ponds, and finding many fewer birds than I saw here two days earlier, we exited the refuge and entered the main part via the wildlife drive.  We drove the road out to the back loop and then walked the loop trail around one of the northern ponds in search of more shorebirds.  We saw many more coots here, most of the teal, and a number of yellowlegs.  Given that there seemed to be many fewer birds than I saw here two days earlier, our search of the area today was rather superficial and I did not try to count the shorebirds as carefully as I had done before.  It was clear, with a mild (10 knot) breeze from the west, and temperatures probably in the upper 80s to low 90s.  3:30-5:00 pm.

Howard King and I wandered around Prado Regional Park in search of a few target species that were known to be present (Least Bittern and Grasshopper Sparrow) or which were moving through the area in numbers (Black Swift).  We easily saw both the bittern and the sparrow but despite much time scanning the swallow flocks, the only swifts we were able to locate were White-throated.  We began our visit by walking along the northwestern shore of the lake scanning the clumps of Cattails and Bulrushes in search of the bitterns.  As it turned out, we had to walk much of the way around the northernmost cove of the lake and back before I spotted a bittern across from where we had parked.  After studying the bittern, we drove over to the campground, from which we walked to the southeast through grassy fields with patches of herbaceous vegetation.  We worked our way almost to Cucamonga Avenue before we located two sparrows singing on a grassy slope with scattered stalks.  After looking at one of the sparrows we made our way down to and then for a short distance along the edge of the riparian corridor, where we had quite a few birds despite the low temperatures and constant wind.  It began raining lightly as we worked our way back towards the campground (enough to get us a little wet), and we even had some hail, but the precipitation ended before we made it back to our vehicle.  We ended our visit by scanning the large flocks of swallows hoping to see a Black Swift.  We managed to find most of the expected breeding species but we did not find any obvious migrants apart from a Bank Swallow.  It was mostly cloudy, with a brief period of light rain and some hail, moderately breezy (with a 10-20 knot breeze from the west or southwest), and cold, with the temperatures increasing from the low 50s only to the upper 50s.  7:30-10:45 am.----California Ground-Squirrel - 6.

LOCALITY: Seacoast Drive to Tijuana River mouth
TRIP COMMENTS: A first-cycle Glaucous Gull was at the Tijuana River mouth at 8:30 --this morning. This is most likely the bird first reported on 7 Feb. by --Robert Patton and others. When first seen the gull was --loafing/foraging with other gulls on the beach at the mouth itself --(not on the flats NE of the mouth). It started  flying/foraging along --the beach south of the river mouth but turned around and flew/foraged --with other gulls just north of the river mouth for a short while. A --Peregrine that had been present the whole time took off and flushed --the terns/shorebirds which in turn spooked the gulls and the Glaucous --headed north. To further ensure no gulls would returned a lady with an --off-leash dog came jogging down the beach (this was the first --pedestrian I had seen all morning). As I was leaving the first --helicopters started doing their endless circles.----I checked IB and the area north of Camp Surf immediately after getting --back from the river mouth but did not see the gull. A scan of the --interior levees of saltworks from 8th St and a check of J St in Chula --Vista later did not produce anything.

LOCALITY: San Dieguito River Park, Bernardo Bay Natural Area
TRIP COMMENTS: Louis Bevier and I joined a group including Van Remsen, Gary Graves, Andrew Kratter, and graduate students Haw Chuan Lim and Karl Mokross, on a visit to the southern shore of Lake Hodges.  While here, we were also loosely associated with another group that included Mike Andersen, Pete Hosner, Matt Brady, and several others.  We began at Rancho Bernardo Community Park and walked out through grasslands and some sage scrub to the lakeshore in search of grebes and ducks.  After scanning the lake, including the arm to the southwest in which dead snags obscured many of the ducks, we walked back, along the way checking the recently burned, riparian corridor, and then we spent some time looking for California Gnatcatchers on a nearby slope of sage scrub that seemed to be dominated by California Buckwheat (Eriogonum fasciculatum) and California Sagebrush (Artemisia californica).  It was partly cloudy with generally high clouds, a mild (5-10 knot) breeze from the northwest, and temperatures in the low 60s.  2:00-4:25 pm.----Louis and I missed a number of birds reported by Van (his numbers included below in brackets), but this may have been in part the result of our leaving somewhat earlier than the others.  Moreover, Mike, Pete, and their group also saw an immature male Vermilion Flycatcher along the riparian corridor, and an early Cliff Swallow, both of which we missed.----Coyote - 1 (wandering along the far shore of the lake, apparently carrying a turtle shortly before I saw it);--California Ground-Squirrel - 25 (calling);--turtle sp. - 1 (the others saw the coyote carrying an unidentified turtle).

LOCALITY: San Diego River--estuary (Old Sea World Dr.)
TRIP COMMENTS: It is early-to-mid fall, and the ducks have finally arrived, many, both males and females, wigeon and mallard being most common, then being pintails, teal, and ruddies.  I''ve seen a few bird I''ve never seen or haven''t seen in a long time at the estuary, like Belted Kingfisher and Clapper Rail. An amazing avian drama unfolded in a Red-tail-0sprey attack, the Osprey leaving with a fish, the hawk being left to be marauded by two American Crows. There was a good number of raptors at the estuary today. I may have seen the same hawk twice, one being see closely sitting above the highway (with a whitish breast). It was soon evening, with quite a few clouds, but only partly overcast.--"A very nice trip!"----NOTE: Was on the SOUTH SIDE of the Southern Wildife Preserve, mostly east of the Sunset Cliffs bridge.

TRIP COMMENTS: We had made the trip to see the Ivory Gull a local rarity just to the south.
Did not see the Ivory Gull.

Larry Sansone, Andrew Howe, and I joined a large number of others on the beach between the west end of Grand Avenue and the mouth of Pismo Creek.  Our target was an adult Ivory Gull that had been found here two days earlier.  Given that the gull was already being seen when we arrived about a half-hour after dawn, and that it remained in view for almost our entire visit, I must admit that I did not look carefully at most of the other birds present.  This list may therefore be somewhat incomplete, even though there were not all that many birds present on the open beach along which we concentrated our efforts.  I spent most of my time just north of Grand Avenue, but we did once drive north to Pismo Creek (where we scanned the creek mouth from the north end and then checked the beach both to the south and north as far as the pier), and I once walked up the beach from Grand Avenue to the southern end of the creek mouth.  Although we had a few land birds, either in the parking lots or along the beach, our search was primarily of birds on the beach itself.  I did not spend much time scanning offshore, something that was further complicated by moderately high surf.  Also present at times were Tom Edell, Brad Schram, Mike Stiles, Jim Royer, Maggie Smith, Dave Lawrence, John Sterling, Jim Lomax, John Luther, Kathryn Parker, Dick Norton, Ken Hollinga, Todd McGrath, Paul Lehman, Guy McCaskie, Brian Sullivan, Nick Lethaby, Don DesJardin, Vic Muryama, Stanley Walens, Nick and Mary Freeman, Lori and Mark Conrad, and many, many others.  It was mostly to partly cloudy, with a brief period of partially sunny conditions mid-morning and essentially a full overcast as we were leaving.  It was also dry during most of our visit, but with a drizzle beginning at about 12:45 pm.  As I recall, there was also a mild (5-10 knot) breeze at times, and temperatures probably ranged from the mid-50s to the low 60s.  7:45 am - 1:00 pm.--Others saw a Merlin fly overhead off Grand Avenue just before we arrived.

TRIP COMMENTS: The weather was  partly cloudy and mild, winds rising to 14mph. Temp was 55 when we arrived. Tide was low, -0.6'' at 11:00 a.m. We began at the field west of the museum. Best bird there was a Western Kingbird, sallying out from high in the eucs. From the Merchant Marine overlook, we saw an Osprey on one of the posts off the beach, so we wended our way down there. In addition to the Osprey, there were many shorebirds, including about 700 Western Sandpipers. We walked the promenade to the area behind Peninsula Humane, then back through the picnic area. There were NO Canada Geese on the lawn. --We walked back up to the field, and checked the overlooks, then drove over to the Yacht Club lot. We walked out to the PG&E Marsh, where we had the usual suspects: one American Coot, 11 Green-winged Teal, Mallards, one Spotted Sandpiper, Killdeer. We checked the towers for raptors without seeing any, but somehow a Peregrine appeared and made for the mudflats. The sandpipers fled in huge clouds. When they resettled, we counted 5-6000 of them. We walked out to the end of the path alongside the marina. On the marina shore, there were Least Sandpipers, a few Dunlin, and a dozen Black Turnstones in alternate plumage. As we turned south around the end of the mudflat, there were a dozen Surfbirds on the shore, also in breeding plumage. Nice! All the birds are just gorgeous right now. The wind picked up, and we went home.

Coyote Point Big Day, Francis Toldi and me.  Not a bad day, given that there were almost no migrants.  Weather delightfully clear, although sometimes windy and a touch cold.  That held migrants down.  We had a great half-day though, and I learned a lot regarding Coyote Point and how to bird it.
